Currently, the various lists of pages (for example, the "List Pages" view of a space) don't allow you to select a sort column. For example, you might want to sort by Creator, Update Date, Last Modifier, etc.

First off, I really like how preformatted blocks have the gray background and the dashed border.

I'm pulling in a lot of content from JSPWiki and I'm glad that the syntax is pretty close to Confluence.  There is on difference, though, that I think Confluence should adopt.

What in Confluence you do by this:
{noformat}preformatted piece of text{noformat}

In JSPWiki you do by this:
{{{
preformatted piece of text
}}}

I see two ways the JSPWiki way is better.  One is you have a clear begin and end of the preformatted block. Two, and more importantly, the preformatted block can appear in the source exactly as it does in the output.  Ie. no need to offset the first line with "{noformat}".  And currently, if I put a newline after "{noformat}" it appears in the output box.

Cheers,
Turadg

I made a page with:

{{{
#!/bin/sh
}}}

And it renders as exactly that.  The triple-braces print and the /bin/sh line is in proportional font.

